{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7e026abe-2434-42e9-a2dc-f9089c4a92e2","content":"Create `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project ...` to start your server.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command` with the path to the executable and drop the `args`.\n\nMake sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC messages to **stdout** and logs/diagnostics to **stderr** (not stdout), or Copilot won't be able to parse the responses.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"310bced9-6c42-4799-aeda-0255cb5653f2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user says they built it. They're asking how to configure `mcp.json` — this is a configuration question, not a \"build it for me\" request. Let me provide the answer.\n\nFor a C# MCP server using stdio transport (which is the standard for local MCP servers), the `mcp.json` configuration in VS Code would look like:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis file goes in `.vscode/mcp.json` in the workspace root.","outputTokens":442,"requestId":"F044:97105:119D6EB:13FBB80:69F94123"},"id":"08a68636-7e59-4ecd-b069-f7558e7db7df","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:00:29.548Z","parentId":"0a79b72b-d1e5-4a7f-be34-fade43473bbf"}
